 in American history-including slavery, the Creek War, the founding of the Cherokee Nation and subsequent removal of Native Americans along the Trail of Tears, and the Civil War. This is the gripping story of their lives, in slavery and in freedom. Meticulously crafted from historical and literary sources, Ties That Bind vividly portrays the members of the Shoeboots family. Doll emerges as an especially poignant character, whose life is mostly known through the records of things done to her-her purchase, her marriage, the loss of her children-but also through her moving petition to the federal government for the pension owed to her as Shoe Boots's widow. A sensitive rendition of the hard realities of black slavery within Native American nations, the book provides the fullest picture we have of the myriad complexities, ironies, and tensions among African Americans, Native Americans, and whites in the first half of the nineteenth century. Updated with a new preface and an appendix of key primary sources, this remains an essential book for students of Native American history, African American history, and the history of race and ethnicity in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxGeorgia. 0aAfrican AmericansxKinshipxGeorgia. 0aAfrican AmericansxKinshipzGeorgia. 0aAfrican AmericanszGeorgia. 0aBlacksxRelations with IndiansxGeorgia. 0aBlackszGeorgiaxRelations with Indians. 0aCherokee IndiansxHistoryx19th century. 0aCherokee IndiansxHistoryy19th century. 0aCherokee IndiansxKinship. 0aCherokee IndiansxMixed descent. 0aIndian slavesxHistoryx19th centuryxGeorgia. 0aIndian slaveszGeorgiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / African American .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is